explanations.200 OK: The request was successful, and the server returned the expected response.
explanations.201 Created: The request was successful, and a new resource was created as a result.
explanations.202 Accepted: The request has been received but is still being processed.
explanations.204 No Content: The request was successful, but there is no content to return.
explanations.301 Moved Permanently: The resource has been permanently moved to a new URL.
explanations.302 Found: The resource has been temporarily moved to a different URL.
explanations.304 Not Modified: The resource has not been modified since the last request.
explanations.400 Bad Request: The server could not understand the request due to invalid syntax.
explanations.401 Unauthorized: Authentication is required to access the requested resource.
explanations.403 Forbidden: The client does not have permission to access the requested resource.
explanations.404 Not Found: The server could not find the requested resource.
explanations.405 Method Not Allowed: The request method is not supported for the requested resource.
explanations.408 Request Timeout: The server timed out waiting for the request.
explanations.409 Conflict: The request could not be completed due to a conflict with the current state of the resource.
explanations.410 Gone: The resource is no longer available and has been permanently removed.
explanations.415 Unsupported Media Type: The server does not support the requested media type.
explanations.429 Too Many Requests: The client has sent too many requests in a given period of time.
explanations.500 Internal Server Error: The server encountered an error and could not complete the request.
explanations.501 Not Implemented: The server does not support the requested functionality.
explanations.502 Bad Gateway: The server received an invalid response from an upstream server.
explanations.503 Service Unavailable: The server is temporarily unable to handle the request.
explanations.504 Gateway Timeout: The server did not receive a timely response from an upstream server.
